# SightLine — Product Requirements Document (PRD)

## Overview
Build a real-time vision assistant for blind people using Meta Ray-Ban smart glasses. The glasses camera captures the world, an AI vision model describes what it sees, and ElevenLabs gives it a natural human voice that plays back through the glasses speakers.

This is a 24-hour hackathon project for Hack for Humanity at Santa Clara University. There are 2 coders. The tech stack must use AMD hardware, ElevenLabs voice AI, and Meta Ray-Ban glasses to be eligible for sponsor prizes.

## Architecture

```
Meta Ray-Ban Glasses (streaming live to Instagram)
        │
        │ User views the IG Live in Chrome on laptop
        ▼
┌─────────────────────────┐
│  Screen Capture Script   │  ← Python script screenshots the IG Live
│  (capture_screen.py)     │     video area in Chrome every 2-3 seconds
└───────────┬─────────────┘
            │ base64 JPEG frames
            ▼
┌─────────────────────────┐
│  Backend Server          │  ← FastAPI running on AMD Developer Cloud
│  (server.py)             │
│                          │
│  ├─ Vision Pipeline      │  ← Llama 3.2 Vision (11B) via vLLM on AMD GPU
│  │                       │     Fallback: Google Gemini Flash 2.0 (free)
│  │                       │
│  ├─ Context Memory       │  ← Stores last 5 descriptions so follow-up
│  │                       │     questions work ("what color was it?")
│  │                       │
│  └─ ElevenLabs Voice     │  ← Converts descriptions to natural speech
└───────────┬─────────────┘
            │ audio response (base64 MP3)
            ▼
┌─────────────────────────┐
│  Phone Bridge            │  ← Simple web app on phone browser
│  (bridge/index.html)     │     Plays audio → Bluetooth → glasses speakers
│                          │     Also has mic input for voice Q&A
└─────────────────────────┘
```

## How the Screen Capture Works

The Meta glasses livestream to Instagram. We open that livestream in Chrome on a laptop. A Python script uses the `mss` library to screenshot a specific region of the screen (where the video is) every 2-3 seconds. Each screenshot is resized, converted to base64, and POSTed to the backend.

This approach bypasses the need to decode Instagram's stream URL (which they block). It's reliable and low-latency (~5-8 seconds end-to-end).

## Components to Build

### Component 1: Screen Capture Script (`capture/capture_screen.py`)

**Purpose:** Continuously screenshot the Instagram Live video from Chrome and send frames to the backend.

**Requirements:**
- Use `mss` library to capture a configurable screen region
- User must be able to set the region coordinates (top, left, width, height) — provide a helper script `find_region.py` that takes a full screenshot so the user can determine coordinates
- Capture a frame every N seconds (configurable, default 3)
- Resize frames to max 1024px on longest side before sending (saves bandwidth and processing time)
- Convert frames to base64 JPEG
- POST each frame to the backend's `/describe` endpoint
- Smart filtering: if the scene hasn't changed much, skip redundant descriptions
- Print descriptions to terminal as they come back for debugging
- Support a `--dry-run` mode that captures frames but doesn't send them (for testing coordinates)
- Support a `--save-frames` flag to save captured frames to disk for debugging

**Also provide:**
- `find_region.py` — takes a full screenshot, saves it, and tells user how to find coordinates
- `test_capture.py` — captures one frame, sends to Gemini Flash to verify vision works, optionally tests ElevenLabs voice output

**Dependencies:** `mss`, `Pillow`, `httpx`

### Component 2: Backend Server (`backend/server.py`)

**Purpose:** FastAPI server that receives image frames, runs them through the vision model, generates speech, and returns audio.

**Endpoints:**

#### `GET /health`
Returns server status, whether vision model is loaded, whether voice is connected.

#### `POST /describe`
Request body:
```json
{
  "image": "base64_encoded_jpeg",
  "mode": "general|ocr|navigation|safety",
  "session_id": "string"
}
```
Response:
```json
{
  "description": "There are two people ahead of you at a table...",
  "safety_alerts": ["stairs", "vehicle"],
  "audio_url": "data:audio/mpeg;base64,...",
  "latency_ms": 1200
}
```

**Mode-specific system prompts:**
- `general` — Full scene description. Priority: safety hazards → people → spatial layout → text/signs → other details. Use spatial language ("to your left", "ahead of you"). Keep to 2-3 sentences.
- `ocr` — Read ALL text visible in the image. Signs, labels, menus, screens, documents. Read exactly as written.
- `navigation` — Navigation info only. Clear path? Obstacles? Stairs/curbs? Doors open/closed? Use clock directions ("obstacle at 2 o'clock").
- `safety` — Safety concerns only. Moving vehicles, stairs, ledges, wet floors, approaching people. If nothing dangerous: "Path looks clear."

#### `POST /ask`
Request body:
```json
{
  "image": "base64_encoded_jpeg",
  "question": "What does the sign on the wall say?",
  "session_id": "string"
}
```
Response:
```json
{
  "answer": "The sign says Exit with an arrow pointing right.",
  "audio_url": "data:audio/mpeg;base64,...",
  "latency_ms": 800
}
```

Uses context memory from previous descriptions so follow-up questions work.

#### `WebSocket /ws/stream`
For real-time continuous streaming. Client sends frames, server responds with descriptions. Also accepts voice questions mid-stream.

Client sends:
```json
{"type": "frame", "image": "base64..."}
{"type": "question", "text": "What color is the building?"}
```
Server responds:
```json
{"type": "description", "text": "...", "safety_alerts": [...]}
{"type": "answer", "text": "..."}
```

Rate limit: don't describe more than once every 3 seconds even if frames come faster.

#### `GET /bridge`
Serves the phone bridge HTML page.

**Context Memory:**
- Store last 5 descriptions per session_id in a deque
- Include last 3 descriptions in the system prompt for continuity
- This allows follow-up questions like "what color was it?" to work

**CORS:** Allow all origins (hackathon — phone bridge needs to connect from any IP)

### Component 3: Vision Module (`backend/vision.py`)

**Purpose:** Interface to the Llama 3.2 Vision model running on AMD Cloud.

**Requirements:**
- Support two backends:
  - `vllm`: For AMD Developer Cloud. vLLM serves an OpenAI-compatible API at `http://localhost:8001/v1`. Send chat completion requests with image_url in base64 format.
  - `ollama`: For local development. Ollama serves at `http://localhost:11434`. Use `/api/generate` endpoint with images array.
- Accept base64 JPEG images, system prompt, and optional user prompt
- Return text description
- Max 200 tokens per response (keep descriptions concise for blind users)
- Temperature 0.3 (factual, not creative)
- Graceful error handling — if model isn't ready, return a helpful message instead of crashing
- Auto-reconnect if model server comes up after the backend starts

**Include setup instructions as comments:**
- How to start vLLM with Llama 3.2 Vision on AMD Cloud
- How to start Ollama locally for testing
- How to switch between backends (single config variable)

### Component 4: Gemini Fallback (`backend/vision_gemini_fallback.py`)

**Purpose:** Drop-in replacement for vision.py using Google Gemini Flash 2.0 (free tier). Use this if vLLM/AMD setup takes too long.

**Requirements:**
- Same class interface as VisionProcessor (same `initialize()` and `describe()` methods)
- Uses `google-generativeai` library
- Gemini Flash 2.0 model (`gemini-2.0-flash`)
- Free tier: 1500 requests/day (more than enough for a hackathon)
- User just needs to swap one import line in server.py to switch

### Component 5: Voice Module (`backend/voice.py`)

**Purpose:** ElevenLabs text-to-speech integration.

**Requirements:**
- Use ElevenLabs API to convert text descriptions to speech
- Use `eleven_turbo_v2_5` model (fastest, lowest latency)
- Default voice: Rachel (ID: `21m00Tcm4TlvDq8ikWAM`) — warm and clear
- Voice settings: stability 0.7, similarity_boost 0.8, style 0.2 (neutral/calm)
- Return audio as base64-encoded MP3 data URL
- Also support streaming audio for lower time-to-first-byte
- Include a `list_voices()` method

**Include instructions for setting up ElevenLabs Conversational Agent** (the more impressive approach where the agent handles full dialogue, not just TTS):
- How to create the agent in the ElevenLabs dashboard
- What system prompt to use for the agent
- How to integrate with the phone bridge

### Component 6: Phone Bridge (`bridge/index.html`)

**Purpose:** Web app that runs on the phone's browser. Connects the backend to the glasses speakers. This is the glue between the AI backend and the physical glasses.

**Requirements:**
- Single HTML file with embedded CSS and JS (no build step)
- Dark theme, mobile-optimized, large touch targets
- Clean, modern UI

**Features:**
- **Status indicators:** Show connection status for server, WebSocket, and audio
- **Three modes:**
  - IG Live Stream mode (default) — works with the screen capture script
  - Phone Camera mode (fallback) — uses the phone's rear camera directly via `getUserMedia` with `facingMode: 'environment'`. Captures frames at configurable intervals and sends to backend.
  - Photo Watch mode — for the "Hey Meta, take a photo" approach
- **Start/Stop button** — big, easy to tap
- **Ask a Question button** — uses Web Speech API (`webkitSpeechRecognition`) for voice input. Sends the transcribed question + latest frame to the `/ask` endpoint.
- **Audio playback queue** — plays audio responses sequentially so they don't overlap. Plays through the phone speaker which routes to glasses via Bluetooth.
- **Browser TTS fallback** — if ElevenLabs audio isn't available, use `SpeechSynthesisUtterance` as fallback
- **Activity log** — scrolling list of descriptions with timestamps, latency, and safety alerts. Safety alerts get a red left border.
- **Settings panel:**
  - Server URL (text input)
  - Capture interval (2s, 3s, 5s, 10s dropdown)
  - Description mode (general, navigation, read text, safety dropdown)

